The hypopigmented macules on the chest and abdomen that do not tan with sun exposure suggest a diagnosis of pityriasis versicolor, which is caused by Malassezia yeast. Cutaneous T cell lymphoma presents with more diffuse skin involvement and TYR gene dysfunction in melanocytes would lead to hyperpigmentation. Treponema pallidum infection would present with different skin lesions, such as a rash or ulceration.
